odreads.com/review/show/3705185785">December 20, 2020</a></span></section><section class="ReviewText"><section class="ReviewText__content"><div class="TruncatedText"><div class="TruncatedText__text TruncatedText__text--5" data-testid="contentContainer"><div><span class="Formatted"><b>A spiritual leader is born. </b><br /><br /><i>The Little Light</i> is a story that narrates the journey from life to death... to rebirth. Dipa draws on a vast variety of religions, traditions and mythologies from all over the world. It is a myth of destruction and creation. A story of dying and being reborn. The protagonist--The Little Light--emanates from The Great Light and incarnates in a human body. <br /><br />Traditions all over the world speak of the soul's journey in between realms. While this is a fiction story that is written simply, the author retains the depth and majesty of spiritual teachers and teachings that have come down to us across all ages. <br /><br />Death is a journey. The very concept inspires unshakable fear in so many people. In a world plagued by COVID-19, the world needs a book such as this one. A book to help souls accept the inevitability of death and accept that it is not the end of our existence. <br /><br />You can read this book at many levels. Humor, philosophy and spiritual thought is interspersed throughout the book. I strongly felt, while reading this book that Sanatani has the makings of a spiritual leader. In religious traditions, many view life as suffering. And while Sanatani does not negate, deny or diminish this in anyway--she also portrays life as born of unbounded compassion. That neither suffering nor pain can be avoided. That all experiences--human and non-human--bring us closer to the Creator from which we emanated. <br /><br />I highly recommend this book to those seeking a spiritual awakening. The Little Light will take you on a journey that brings much-needed light to your soul. </span></div></div></div></section></section><section c