lass="TruncatedText__text TruncatedText__text--5" data-testid="contentContainer"><div><span class="Formatted">The denial of death is the denial of life. In <i>The Little Light</i>, Sanatani takes us on a journey in the in between. The Tibetans call this state the Bardo, the realm in between realms. The Egyptians called it the afterlife. The Christians have called it eternity. Spirituality cannot and should not be a practise relegated to the old folks. It is a part of life. A part of all our lives.<br /><br />We ignore death, till it consumes us and leaves wondering where our loved ones went. We are unable to accept death, no more than we are unable to accept to life. We believe we are owners, as opposed to mere stewards in this world.<br /><br />In the current climate of COVID-19, the current generation has experienced death on an unprecedented scale. As the current generations of the world, we have been living selfishly, with an unending pool of desires that only deepens. Even in this era of COVID-19, we think someone else is to blame for our woes. <br /><br />Dipa's book allowed me to view death and life with a new perspective. It is written simply. One does not require years of religious study to understand the message that the book is trying to convey. If you're looking for a book on spirituality that doesn't require years and years of vigorous study, this book is great start to awaken your soul. <br /><br />I look forward to seeing what comes of Dipa's career in the coming years. A big thank you to the author for writing this gem of a book. I wish her success and happiness in her writing career. </span></div></div></div></section></section><section class="ReviewCard__tags"></section><footer class="SocialFooter"><div data-testid="stats" class="SocialFooter__statsContainer"><div class="Button__container"><button type="button" class="Button Button--inline Button--small Button--subdued"><span class="Button__labelItem">13 likes</span></button></div></div><div data-t